{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hines_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280659216/1927010101/0029.xml":{"full_text":"28\n1927 EMPLOYMENT\nSURPLUS LOOMING\nCut in Government Forces\nLeaves Many Idle\nin Capital.\nEmployment in the District of\nQplumbia in 1927 has a \u201cnot altogether\nsatisfactory\u201d outlook, as there is a\ngeneral surplus of labor apparent\nwhich may increase, the Federal em\nployment director for Washington de\nclared today in a forecast of conditions\nfor the year.\nThe reduction of Government per\nsonnel carried out through 1926 has\nleft many men and women, principally\nclerical workers, without employment,\nand it is not regarded as likely tnat\nthere will be enough employment op\nportunities during 1927 to absorb these\nunemployed.\n\u201cWashington not being an industrial\ncity, the labor demand comes neces\nsarily from the bakeries, laundries,\nice cream factories, railroad terminals\nand retail establishments,\u201d the direc\ntor said.\n\"From all reports, no increase in\nthe demand for these workers is ex\npected in 1927 over that which existed\nin 1926. It is predicted that the\nvolume of building will not be as large,\nwhich will make it harder for un\nskilled labor to secure work. The pro\nposed erection of public buildings will\ndo much to relieve unemployment\namong skilled and unskilled construc\ntion workers. Street work and other\ncity improvements will offer employ\nment to a large number of men\nthroughout the year.\u201d\n$60,000,000 for Building.\nPrivate building operations in\nWashington in the first 11 months of\nthe year involved the expenditure of\nmore than $60,000,000, according to\nCommerce Department figures.\nIndustrial prospects for 1927 in\nMaryland Indicate a slight decrease in\nsome lines of manufacture, according\nto the Maryland director. The de\nmand for skilled labor, however,\nshould be as great as in 1926, or al\nmost to the saturation point. Plenty\nof work for unskilled labor is fore\ncast, with indications pointing to a\nbuilding program quite as large as\nthat of 1926, and full employment of\nthe building tradesmen during the\ngreater part of 1927 is forecast. An\nincrease in expenditures for public\nworks is thought probable.\nVirginia employment prospects dur\ning 1927 are regarded by the State\ndirector as somewhat better than dur\ning 1926. Opening of new silk mills,\nknitting mills, additions to furniture\nfactories and to fruit and preserving\nplants will give employment to many\nskilled and unskilled workers. While\nthere may be a decline in soft coal\nproduction, an increase in the devel\nopment and production of Virginia\nanthracite is anticipated. A large\namount of public improvement work\nis planned, and the State Highway\nDepartment will have about $8,000,000\navailable for road construction work.\nThe West Virginia director declared\nthat prolonged activity in steel manu\nfacture, coal mining and volume of\nbuilding forecasts a prosperous year\nfor the State.\nConditions Good Nationally.\nIn a foreword to the reports of\nState directors, Francis I. Jones, em\nployment director general, said the\nbusiness outlook for the year now\nbeginning indicates a healthy con\ndition throughout the country.\nHe said:\n\u201cThe year that has just passed\ninto history waa remarkable for its\nindustrial activity; its building con\nstruction, which almost equaled the\nphenomenal record of 1925; the soil\nproducing bumper crops; railroads\nscoring new high records; the auto\nmobile and truck industry with the\nbanner year to its credit, and road\nconstruction on a large scale, all re\nflecting in a tremendous volume of\nemployment.\n\u201cThe business outlook for the year\nnow beginning, according to our sur\nvey, indicates a healthy condition\nthroughout the country. Optimism\nand confidence prevail; capital and\nlabor have a better understanding,\nand with no apparent dark spots on\nthe industrial horizon, the volume of\nemployment should equal, if not\nsurpass, the year. Just closed.\u201d\nBLAME AUTO FOR WRECK.\nDriver Held Responsible for De\nrailing Train at Crossing.\nThat most unusual of railway ac\ncidents\u2014-derailment of a passenger\ntrain by an automobile\u2014was held by\nthe Interstate Commerce Commission\nIn a specific case today to be the\nfault of the driver of an automobile\nwhich was struck by a Louisville and\nNashville train at Hendersonville,\nTenn., November 16.\nThe two occupants of the automo\nbile were killed and in the resulting\nderailment of the train, twelve pas\nsengers and four dining car em\nployes were injured. The accident\nis held unique in that the automo\nbile usually comes off second best in\nsuch cases, while in this case the train\nwas derailed.\nOn the same day a head end col\nlision between two maintenance of\nway motor cars occurred on the same\nrailroad, resulting in the death of six\nemployes and Injury to 14 more. This\naccident, the commission said, was\ncaused by poor judgment exercised\nby a section foreman who moved his\ncar in a direction opposite to his in\nstructions, and by another section\nforeman who failed to keep his car\nwithin the prescribed speed limit.\n\u201cPADLOCK\u201d IS SOUGHT.\nOwner of Delioatessen Store Placed\nUnder Dry Charges.\nApplication for a \u201cpadlock\u201d injunc\ntion has been made to the Dis\ntrict Supreme Court by United States\nAttorney Gordon and Assistant United\nStates Attorney Harold W. Orcutt\nagainst Morris Cohn, owner of a deli\ncatessen store at 1510 Fourteenth\nstreet northwest. An injunction to\nprevent the handling of liquor was\nalso requested against bis three clerks,\nJulian Hathe, Abraham Jawfe and\nDavid Miller.\nCohn, the petition sets forth, had\nbeen restrained from dealing in liquor\nwhen he occupied a place on Eighth\nstreet southeast.\nSEEKS INJUNCTION.\nAntonio Cupido Resists Deporta\ntion to Italy.\nAntonio Cupido has asked the\nDistrict Supreme Court for an in\njunction against James ,1. Davis, Sec\nretary of Labor, to prevent his depor\ntation to Italy. Cupido was a former\nseaman and came to this country\nMay 4, 1923, as a member of the crew\nof a British freighter from Buenos\nAlroz, but he is new a steel mill work\ner at Pittsburgh. lie says he has de\nclared his Intention to become an\nAmerican citizen and attacks the va\nlidity of the deportation order, made\nKeptember 7 last, as being more than\nthree years after his arrival. He is\nrepresented by Attorney Ward Bon\nsalL\nThe Tomato,\no o\n\"Touch not that fruit,\u201d the old man\nsaid, \u201cor It will make you 111\u201d; I\u2019d\nreached for a tomato red, upon the\nwindow sill. There It had ripened in\nthe sun, whose beams upon it beat;\nit looked to me, a greedy one, like\nsomething good to eat. \u201cThe ripe\ntomato\u2019s jassing fair,\u201d he said with\nboding grin; \u201cbut shun it, for It is a\nsnare, a pitfall and a gin. ft\u2019s loaded\nwith a poisoned juice that wise men\nmust eschew; if shallowed it will soon\nproduce a cancer, maybe two. It hath,\nlike sin, a gaudy charm, beguiling to\nthe eye, but if you est It, with alarm\nyou find you\u2019re billed to die. A wast\ning sickness clogs your veins, so that\nthe blood won\u2019t flow, and you are full\nof aches and pains till to the grave\nyou go.\u201d Thus people talked when I\nwas young about that crimson fruit,\nthat like a deadly adder stung the\nthoughtless, brash galoot. There were\na hundred ghastly tales of youths who\nate and died, who gathered up the\nfruit In pails, and would not be de\nnied. The superstition held for years,\nand countless timid souls beheld the\nfruit with clammy fears, nor touched\nIt save with poles. We have out\ngrown that fool belief, removed the\nsenseless ban; now the tomato is the\nchief of all the green goods clan. The\ndoctors tell us every day, when pmigs\nof sickness goad, \u201cBuy fresh toma\ntoes on a drav, and eat the whole\nblamed load. No better counsel could\nyoM get. with all your hoarded wealth;\ntomatoes are the one best bet, con\ntributing to health.\u201d We eat them\nraw. we eat them fried, we eat them\nfrom a can: and up to date no man\nhas died from following this plan.\nWALT MASON.\ntCooyriirht. 1927.)\nDECREASE OF $17,490,000\nIN ALASKAN MINERALS\nMarked Reduction Due to Drop in\nValues, Not Production,\nDepartment Holds.\nMineral production in Alaska de\nclined to a value of $17,490,000 from\nthe production of 1925, valued at $lB,-\n220,692, the Interior Department has\nannounced. At the same time the\ndepartment said the value of the total\nmineral production of Alaska is more\nthan $570,000,000.\nAlthough the Geological Survey\nestimates of a drop in the 1926 produc\ntion are indicated by the figures re\nvealed today, the decrease In value\nby no means indicates a decrease in\nmining activity or even an equivalent\ndecrease In quantity of certain of the\nmetals produced, the department said.\nConsiderably more than half of the\ndrop in value is directly attributable\nto the lower price of the product,\nwhich was a condition now confined\nto the mining industry in Alaska.\n\u201cEven the current reduced annual\nvalue of the mineral production from\nAlaska is practically two and a half\ntimes the prioe originally paid for the\nentire Territory,\u201d the department de\nclared.\nGenerally mining conditions through\nAlaska were declared encouraging, not\nonly for continuation of production at\nthe present rate but for a gradual in\ncrease, and there are many large\nareas in the territory that have not\nbeen adequately prospected, while\nother promising properties are now\nlying idle because of lack of capital\nfor necessary equipment. The short\nage of enterprising prospectors was\nheld to be a serious drawback, while\nthe need for capital is pressing.\n1932 PROGRAM URGED.\nSterling Would Have Students\nInformed of Historical Facts.\nThe conduct of a national educa\ntional program in institutions of\nlearning throughout the United States\nin connection with the bicentennial\ncelebration in 1932 of George Wash\nington\u2019s birth, as a means of familiar\nizing the younger generation with the\nprinciples upon which this country\u2019s\ngovernment was founded, was advo\ncated by former Senator Thomas\nSterling of South Dakota at a lunch\neon of the Round Table Club in the\nUniversity Club yesterday.\nFrom such a program there would\narise \"a new birth of patriotism In\nthis Nation,\u201d the speaker predicted.\nThe former Senator now is field sec\nretary of the national commission pro\nvided by law to make recommenda\ntions for the bicentennial celebration\nhaving been appointed by President\nCoolidge.\nRev. Dr. Frederick Brown Harris\npastor of Foundry Methodist Episco\npal Church here, and his father, Rev.\nDr. George T. Harris, pastor of the\nChelsea-Ventnor Methodist Episcopal\nChurch of Atlantic City, N. J., were\namong the guests at the luncheon\nctab E pr&.f\" l,W e a nt r th\nHOLIDAY RUM SEIZED.\nPolice Here Get Total of 1,875\nQuarts in Week.\nThe dry enforcement squad of the\nMetropolitan Police Department, head\nby S l r gt George L \u2018ttle. climaxed\nctlvit,es for the year by seizing\n1,875 quarts of intoxicants intended\nfor the holiday trade, according to\nstatistics complied today In the office\nof Maj. Edwin B. Hesse, superin\ntendent.\nWhile the seizures were smaller than\nthose in past years, the police at\ntribute this to the extra precautions\ntaken by the bootleggers at a season\nwhen they knew they would be under\nclose scrutiny.\nTen automobiles and horse-drawn\nvehicles used to convey the forbidden\n\u201chootch\u201d also were seized by the po\nlice during the week and 251 persons\nwere arrested for intoxication, 5 of\nthem for drinking in public and 10 for\ndriving automobiles while under the\nInfluence of liquor. Arrests for sale,\npossession and transportation of in\ntoxicants totaled 76.\nPROGRAM AT HOSPITAL.\nBoys and Girls Entertain Men at\nWalter Reed.\nBoys and girls of Noel House, 1663\nKramer street northeast, entertained\nformer service men at Walter Reed\nHospital last night. The program\nconsisted of dance numbers and a\nplay, entitled \u201cThe Last Rehearsal.\u201d\nThirty-nine children took part.\nRichard Smith had the leading role\nin the play. Those who appeared in\nspecial dances were Elsie Soper,\nCatherine Walter, Phenie King. Mar\ngaret Cooper, Juliann Zetts and\nPriscilla Wener.\nThe entertainment was arranged by\nMiss Loretta Murphy and John E.\nZetts,\nASKS SUIT DISMISSAL.\nThe Medical Society of the District\nof Columbia has asked the Dis\ntrict Supreme Court to dismiss a\nsuit for $200,000 damages filed by Miss\nMary A. Ruthven in connection with\nher detention for some weeks at St.\nElizabeth\u2019s Hospital. Ten similar\nsuits brought by Miss Ruthven\nagainst a number of District officials\nwere thrown out on demurrers.\nThrough Attorney Frederick A.\nFenning, the Medical Society, by Dr.\nCoursen B. Conklin, Its secretary, says\nit has never been known as the Wash\nington Medical and Surgical Associa\ntion, under which name the suit vws\nfiled.\nTHE EVENING STAR. WASHINGTON, I). C\u201e SATUHDAY, .JANiTARY 1. 1927.\nHOOVER FORESEES\nPROSPERITY AHEAD\nDepicts U. S. as Nation With\n\u201cJob\u201d in Hand for\n\u201cMost Everybody.\u201d\nA picture of a prosperous Nation,\nwith a job in prospect for \u201cmost every\nbody\u201d and with the entire Nation bet\nter fed, better housed and better\nclothed than any other nation, was\ndrawn today in a New Year day\nstatement by Secretary Hoover. Re\nviewing the prosperity of 1926, Mr.\nHoover said:\n\u2018\u2018A reply to requests for opinion on\nthe new year\u2019s economic prospects can\nonly be based on the economic cur\nrents already born of the old year.\nNew and unknown currents will enter\nin the new year, so there is no such\nthing as assured economic prophecy.\nHigh Production in 1926.\n\u201cNo one will deny that 1926 has\nshown the highest total production\nand consumption of Industrial com\nmodities of any year in the history of\nthe United States. Except in the tex\ntile Industry and parts of the coal\nindustry. It has been a year of high\ndegree of employment, which has been\naccompanied by the highest peak In\nreal wages, because wage income for\nthe country as a whole has slightly\nincreased and cost of living slightly\ndecreased during the year. Manufac\nturing, the service industries, and\ncommerce generally have continued to\nImprove their methods, to reduce\ncosts, and to Improve services. In\naggregate, each industry appears to\nshow substantial profits except the\ntextile and some parts of the coal in\ndustry. While there has been a slack\nening In production and demand for\nseveral staple lines during the last\nfew weeks, we enter the new year\nwith no consequential overstock of\nmanufactured goods. With the larg-\nest volume of construction during the,\nlast year ever known there may prove\nto be some construction in advance of\nImmediate needs, but slackening In\nthis direction may be partially com-\npensated by the assurance of a larger\namount of public construction during i\nthe next year. Savings of the coun\ntry have shown a steady increase, and\nthere is ample cheap capital available.\nCrop Failures and Other Ills.\n\"The lag of agricultural recovery\nhas continued and has been accentu\nated by distressing crop failures in\nsome localities. Cotton and some fruit\ncrops beyond world demand have\nbrought about prices below the cost\nof production of large areas of those\ncommodities. There is a consequent\nlowered buying power in s\u00bbme agri\ncultural sections.\n\u201cTaking the foreign field as a whole,\nit shows continued progress toward\nbalance of budgets; reduction of float\ning debt; greater stability in currency,\nand somewhat diminished unemploy\nment. The most Important exception\nhas been the results of the British\ncoal strike, which left the world\npoorer by its interruption of the prog\nress of that country, but this is now\nhappily over. Russia shows some eco\nnomic improvement, and China, due\nto international trade relations, still\ncontinues below normal. Each year\nsees progress in European political 1\nrelations, with fear less and less a\ndominating factor.\n\u201cCombining all foreign and domes\ntic tendencies with which we enter the\nnew year, while some of them are not\nso good as we could wish, others are j\nmost hopeful. To those who are in\nterested in the movement of the busi\nness cycle. It is worth remarking that\nItfesolution.\nDecide to\njoin our\nChristmas i/\\\nClub i\n*75 -Day \\g\u00a74\n\nTHE WEEKLY DEPOSITS will soon grow into a fund that will\nenable you to enjoy the greatest of all Holidays to the fullest extent.\nNOW IS THE TIME TO DECIDE\nYOU will never miss the amounts required to keep up the payments.\nYou will be delighted when you get it back in a lump sum just when\nyou need it most.\nJOIN MONDAY\nEast Washington Savings Bank, Lincoln National Bank,\n312 Penna. Ave. S.K. At Branch Only\u2014l7th ft H Sts. N.W.\nNorth Capitol Savings Bank, N't 11 1 \u201c\u201c\"El\nNorth Capitol and H Sts. N.W.\nChevy Chase Saving; Bank. Riggs National Bank.\nConnecticut Ave. and McKinley St. Main Office\u2014l3o3 Penna. Ave.\nPotomac Savings Bank. mh^a'^rCo'iSmhia o \u00dfd*\nWisconsin Ave. and M St. N.W. 14th SC and Park Rd.\nWashington Savings Rank. 7th and I Sts N.W.\n10th and Grant Place N.W. National Savings and Trust Co.,\nAmerican Security St Trust Co.. orner 10th Ave N.W.\nMain Office\u2014l3th Sc Penna. Ave. N.W'. Federal-American National Bank,\nBranched\u2014Central: 7tb St Mass. Ave. IMh and G Sts. N.W.\na v \u00aba|i s The Anaeostla Bank.\nNOUtIIHMt dill w K Nt\u00df- t >AAA \\lrhfll\u00df Atra WIT\nNorthwest: 1140 15th St. _ ~000 Nichols Ave. S.K.\nRank of Commerce and Savings.\nFranklin National Bank. Seventh and E Sts. N.W.\nMain tiOlve\u2014-Penna. Ave. at loth Bt. Washington Coan ft Trust Co..\nBranch Office 1111 Conn. Ave. Main Office\u2014Ninth and F Sts. ff.W.\nMcLachlen Banking Corporation, Branch Office\u2014l7th and <1 Sts. N.W.\nMain Office\u2014loth and G Sts. N.W. Farmers ft Mechanics\u2019 National Bank.\nBranch Office\u2014l3oo B St. S.W. Thirty-second und M Sts. N.W.\nSecurity Savings ft Commercial Bank, Park Savings Bank,\nNinth and G Sts. N.W. Fourteenth and Kenyon Sts. N.W.\nDistrict National Bank. Commercial National Bank.*\nMain Office\u2014l4oo G St. N.W. Fourteentnand G Sts. N.W.\nAve. ft K St. Washlmrton Mechanics Savings Bank,\n9th and New York Ave. N.W. Main \u2014Klrhtli and G Sts. B.E.\nColumbia National Bank. Branches\u2014Ninth ft E. Capitol Sts.\n911 F St. N.W. 3008 Georgia Ave. N.W.\nChristmas Savings Clubs are maintained by the members of the District of Columbia\nBankers Association for the benefit of the community and not as a source of profit.\nTODAY'S AMUSEMENTS.\nNational\u2014\u201c Love In a Mist,\u201d com\nedy, at 8:20 p.m. Matinee at 2:20 p.m.\nPoll's\u2014\" The Vagabond King,\u201d musi\ncal play, at 8:20 p.m. Matinee at 2:20\np.m.\nBelasco \u2014Mrs. Flske in \u201cGhosts,\u201d at\n8:20 p.m. Matinee at 2:20 p.m.\nKeith's\u2014\u2019\u2019Dancing Derby,\u201d vaude\nville, at 2:15 and 8:15 p.m.\nEarle\u2014\" Gerber\u2019s Giggles,\u201d vaude\nville, continuous 1:30 to 11 p.m.\nBtrand-\"Frolics of 1927.\" vaude\nville, continuous 12:30 to 11 p.m.\nWardman Park \u2014St. Patrick Play\ners, \"What! No Prince?\u201d musical com\nedy, at 8:15 p.m.\nGayety\u2014\" Dave Mario n\u2019s Own\nShow,\u201d burlesque, at 2:15 and 8:15 p.m.\nMutual\u2014\" Dimpled Darlings,\u201d bur\nlesque, at 2:20 and 8:20 p.m.\nMetropolitan \"Twlnkletoes,\u201d at\n11:46 a.m., 1:35, 3:40, 6:35, 7:50 and\n9:60 p.m.\nPalace \u2014\u201cLove\u2019s Blindness,\u201d at 10:60\na.m., 12:10, 2:15, 4:30, 6:45, 7:60 and\n10:05 p.m.\nRialto- \"Taxi! Taxi!\u201d at 11:25 a.m.,\n1:15, 3:25, 6:15, 7:25 and 9:40 p.m.\nColumbia \u201cWe\u2019re In the Navy\nNow,\u201d at 11:36 a.m., 1:15, 2:55, 4:45,\n6:25, 8:05 and 9:55 p.m.\nTivoli\u2014\"The Strong Man,\u201d at\n2:26, 4:15, 6:10, 8 and 9:50 p.m.\nAmbassador\u2014\u201c The Family Up\nstairs,\u201d at 2:40, 4:30, 6:15, 8:05 and\n9:55 p.m.\nCentral\u2014\u201c After Marriage.\u201d at 12:30\n2, 3:30, 6, 6:30, 8 and 9:40 p.m.\nLincoln (Colored)\u2014-\u201cParadise,\u201d 2 to\n11 p.m.\nwe> have had no Inflation In commodi\nties, as prices have decreased rather\nthan increased during the year. More\nover, the elasticity of credit through\nthe Federal Reserve System, the ab\nsence of undue stocks of commodities,\nthe greatly enlarged information serv\nices of the country, and wider under\nstanding (and thus better common\njudgment and caution) are all protec\ntions against violent movements, such\nas we experienced in former times.\nNation Shows Economic Progress.\n\u201cThe Nation Is making economic\nprogress. Some areas lag behind oth\ners, and discontent with the lag is an\nassurance of a lively sense of initiative\nand the best promise of remedy. Each\nindividual tests the question of pros\nperity by his own setting and natu\nrally applies his own test to his views\nof the economic state of the nation.\nIf we use the more precise term \u2019eco\nnomic progress\u2019 we find we have per\ncapita as the result of the year 1926\nmore and better homes, more electric\nlights and power, more transportation,\nmore roads, more substantial build\nings, more radios and more automo\nbiles, more savings, more life Insur\nance, and more of a lot of things. We\nalso have more educational facilities\nand more per capita circulation of\nnewspapers and magazines than ever\nbefore.\n\u201cAltogether, we enter the new year\nwith a Job in prospect for most every\nbody, with the whole Nation better\nfed, better housed and better clothed\nthan any other nation. The large dis\nappearance of poverty in the chronic\nsense should make us more sensible\nto the remedy of misfortune in the\nindividual sense, and the high recov\nery of Industry and commerce from\nthe losses of the war should make us\nmore sensible so the needs of agricul\nture.\u201d\nAugusta-Aiken Special\nLeaves Washington 7:25 p.m. begin\nning Monday. Excellent tourist hotels\nand golf courses. Southern Railway\nCity Ticket Office, 1510 H St. N.W.\nPhones Main 5633 and 7063.\u2014Adver\ntisement.\nTHREE ENTER PLEAS\nIN LOST LIQUOR SUIT\nFormer Agents Deny Having Part\nIn Removal of Seized\nWet Goods.\nFrank Burke, former chief of secret\nservice men under A. Mitchell Palmer,\nwhile Attorney General, and P. J.\nAhearn and Henry P. Alden, then\nspecial agents of the Department of\nJustice, yesterday filed pleas to the\nsuit of Alonzo E. Bunch In which\nBunch charged the loss of eight cases\nof real whisky and 15 cases of pre\nwar beer. Bunch placed the value\nof the intoxicants at $1,975 and asked\njudgment for that amount against the\ndefendants. .The suit was filed April\n7, 1922.\nThe liquor Is said to have dlsap\npeared from a warehouse after It had\nbeen seized in 1921 under the bone\ndry amendment. A grand Jury inves\ntigated the disappearance of the wet\ngoods and filed a report expressing\ncensure at the disappearance of the\nseized property but failed to accuse\nany particular employe of the De\npartment.\nThrough Attorneys James B. Archer\nand Charles F. Sanford, the three\nmen deny that they had anything to\ndo with the disappearance of the\nliquor. They also point out that the\nliquor had no value In law, as It was\ncontraband.\nFARMER WORKS 11 HOURS.\nExpenses Average $1,598 a Year\nfor Family, Survey Shows.\nBy the Associated Press.\nLiving expenses of farm families\naverage $1,598 a year, the Department\nof Agriculture has determined after a\nsurvey. The sons and daughters cost\nmore to clothe than the farmer and his\nwife, and the daughters\u2019 clothes cost\nmore than the sons\u2019.\nThe average sized family sharing\nthe expense was about 4% persons.\nFood accounted for two-fifths of the\nliving costs; clothing 14.7 per cent;\nrent 12.5 per cent; operation goods,\n13.3 per cent.\nHusbands and wives were credited\nwith an annual expenditure of $59\neach for clothing. The work day was\nfound to be 11.3 hours for the farmer\nand 11.4 for the housewife.\nYouth Shot by Reveler.\nAn unidentified individual, celebrat\ning the advent of the New Year at\nThirteenth and F streets about 12:15\no\u2019clock this morning, accidentally shot\nFrederick Clayton Stafford, 18 years\nold, 732 Eleventh street, who was\npassing near the intersection of the\ntwo streets on his way home. The\nbullet inflicted only a slight wound on\nthe young man\u2019s head.\nWomen in Belgium are going into\npolitics in large numbers and at a re\ncent election in Waret more than half\nthe candidates for office were women.\nAPPY\nNEW YEAR\nTo All Our Friends\nand Patrons.\nE. Morrison Paper Co.\nHouses For Sale and Rent\nJ. Leo Kolb\nWAIN 5027\n923 New York At. 1237 Wisc\u2019n. Av.\nAMUSEMENTS.\nRATIONAL TUNIGHI I\nII I.AHT TIME cn c,\nMADGE KENNEDY\nin\n\u201cLOVE-IN-A-MIST\u201d\nWITH\nSIDNEY BLACKMER\nNEXT WEEK HEATH SKMJNG\nJOHN GOLDEN I'rwritu\nIIDIACD a comic\nROMANCE\nw OF YOUTH\nBy Anne Merrlion and Patterton MaNutt\nWith WALLACE FOBS and UNA\nMERKEL and a Cait of Distinction\nPlay Staged by FRANK CRAVEN\n\"Flga\" kept New York laughing for a year.\nNEXT CONCERT\nPHILHARMONIC\nSOCIETY OF N. Y.\nORCHESTRA\nWagner-Beethoven Program\nWillem Mengelberg, Conductor\nTue*. Jan. 4th\nTickets. *'4.50. *2.00, 51.50. *I.OO\nT. Arthur Smith Bureau, 1330 G\nSt.\u2014ln Kltt\u2019e.\nSEATS SELLING\nFRIEDA\nHEMPEL\nRecital\u2014National Theater Friday,\n\u2022lan. 7. Ticket*, *'4.50, *\u20184.00. *1.50\nand *I.OO\u2014T. Arthur Smith Bureau,\n1330 G St., In Kltt'g.\n1 NEWYEAfc\u2019SDAYf\nTODAY\nTHREE (3) SHOWS\n2:15\n8 5:15\n8:15\nLeaf Performance! of This I\nWeek\u2019! Great Show j\nBXeit Week 1\ni WILL MAHONEY i\n&l%\\ <PkentS MAIN 44844485-M3X/Sg\nPERPETUAL I\nBUILDING\nASSOCIATION j\nPAYS\n5%\nCompo